sqlite_file = 'lahman2014.sqlite'
conn = sqlite3.connect(sqlite_file)

salary_query = "SELECT yearID, sum(salary) as total_payroll, teamID FROM Salaries GROUP BY yearID, teamID"
winning_query = "SELECT yearID, teamID, W as wins, G as games FROM Teams GROUP BY yearID, teamID"

salaries = pd.read_sql(salary_query, conn)
winnings = pd.read_sql(winning_query, conn)

winnings["win_perc"] = (winnings['wins'] / winnings['games'] * 100)

table = pd.merge(winnings, salaries, how='inner', on=['teamID','yearID'])

table

I was able to do this by groupign within the SQL by yearID and teamID for salaries and teamID. I was then able to read the SQL and input it as a dataframe. I created a new column where I then calculated the winning percentage. I was then able to merge the salaries and winnings table using an inner merge. I utilized an inner merge because incase there are any teams/years that do not have any data for total_payroll AND winning percentage, we do not want to use this information. This is because we are analyzing if there is a correlation between the two, so if we do not have information for one of them (no matter the reason) we do not want to utilize that information.

greater_90 = table.copy(deep=True)

fig, ax = plt.subplots()

In [5]:
table['bins'] = pd.cut(x=table['yearID'], bins=5, precision = 0)

groups = table.groupby(['bins'])

for name, group in groups:
    frame = pd.DataFrame(columns=['teamID','mean_payroll', 'mean_winnings'])
    teams = group.groupby(['teamID'])
    
    for name1, group1 in teams:
        frame.loc[len(frame.index)] = [name1,group1['total_payroll'].mean(),group1['win_perc'].mean()]
        
    frame.plot.scatter(x='mean_payroll', y='mean_winnings', title = name, xlabel="Mean Payroll Per Team", ylabel="Mean Winnings Per Team(%)")
    
    for i, txt in enumerate(frame['teamID']):
        plt.annotate(txt, (frame['mean_payroll'][i], frame['mean_winnings'][i]))

    m,b = np.polyfit(frame['mean_payroll'], frame['mean_winnings'],1)
    plt.plot(frame['mean_payroll'], m*frame['mean_payroll']+b)

Code Description: In order to represent the mean winnings and mean payroll over 5 separate time periods, I utilized the pandas cut method to create 5 even sized bins. I then added this as a column to the original table created in problem 1. I then grouped the table by the bins created before. Then, inorder to create a table of the mean of each individual team, I looped through each of the bin groups and grouped that again by the teamID. This allowed me to then grab the mean winnings an payroll for that team for the timeframe. I then added these two values, alongside the teamID, to a new dataframe. I then created a scatterplot out of this new dataframe, added a linear regression line, and added text to each point on the scaterplot to represent the teamID. This allowed us to compare and contrast each team and each trend over a period of time.

When looking at Oakland A's spending efficiency across these time periods, in the beginning years we can see that they were on the average side of the mean payroll compared to other teams. While this payroll did payoff, they slowly increased their payroll as time went on whereas other teams increased it exponentially. That did not effect their winning percentage though. teams = table.groupby(['yearID'])

frame = pd.DataFrame(columns=['yearID','mean_payroll', 'sd_payroll'])

for name, group in teams:
    mean = group['total_payroll'].mean()
    sd = group['total_payroll'].std()
    frame.loc[len(frame.index)] = [name,group['total_payroll'].mean(),group['total_payroll'].std()]
    
table =table.merge(frame, on=['yearID'])
table['standardized_payroll'] = (((table['total_payroll'])-(table['mean_payroll'])) / table['sd_payroll'])
